00:56:15.590 --> 00:56:18.290
AUDIENCE: Thanks so
much for the talk.

00:56:18.290 --> 00:56:21.670
I have a question
about-- so bringing this

00:56:21.670 --> 00:56:25.900
into the workplace, where you
mentioned getting to a flow

00:56:25.900 --> 00:56:29.580
state, and a relationship
with that between-- how

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:32.590
is that necessarily related
to something that is actually

00:56:32.590 --> 00:56:34.190
beneficial in a larger sense?

00:56:37.170 --> 00:56:39.320
A company that makes
cluster bombs that

00:56:39.320 --> 00:56:44.060
wants to function with less
dysfunction in the workplace,

00:56:44.060 --> 00:56:45.680
as one example.

00:56:45.680 --> 00:56:48.690
AUSTIN HILL SHAW: That's
a fantastic question.

00:56:48.690 --> 00:56:52.050
The question, again, is how-- if
we're entering the flow states,

00:56:52.050 --> 00:56:52.950
that's great.

00:56:52.950 --> 00:56:56.050
But what if our outlook is to
build a better bomb, a more

00:56:56.050 --> 00:56:57.980
destructive element?

00:56:57.980 --> 00:57:00.900
So, you know, how to say.

00:57:00.900 --> 00:57:02.870
I love humanity.

00:57:02.870 --> 00:57:05.200
And when I'm working
with individuals,

00:57:05.200 --> 00:57:07.500
what I've recognized
through the years is,

00:57:07.500 --> 00:57:09.400
people want to
love and be loved.

00:57:09.400 --> 00:57:10.767
But hurt people hurt people.

00:57:10.767 --> 00:57:12.100
That comes in the prison system.

00:57:12.100 --> 00:57:16.330
The meanest person in
the yard is the one that

00:57:16.330 --> 00:57:18.530
has been hurt the most, right?

00:57:18.530 --> 00:57:20.650
So you're right.

00:57:20.650 --> 00:57:23.210
A flow state can be
used destructively.

00:57:23.210 --> 00:57:26.370
But the beauty of a flow state,
when it's working actively,

00:57:26.370 --> 00:57:31.470
is it brings forth what
I call transmutation.

00:57:31.470 --> 00:57:33.340
Transmutation is
basically moving--

00:57:33.340 --> 00:57:35.830
it's almost like alchemical,
bringing a base substance

00:57:35.830 --> 00:57:37.430
and making it elevated.

00:57:37.430 --> 00:57:40.950
But in human beings, it means
taking all those hurts become

00:57:40.950 --> 00:57:43.300
bottled up in the
ways we shut away,

00:57:43.300 --> 00:57:45.560
turn away from our
natural creativity

00:57:45.560 --> 00:57:47.050
into addictive patterns.

00:57:47.050 --> 00:57:48.740
We face those
patterns and we step

00:57:48.740 --> 00:57:51.320
back in through the
process of transmutation.

00:57:51.320 --> 00:57:53.760
So one of the highest
expressions of creativity,

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:56.870
in my opinion, is healing.

00:57:56.870 --> 00:58:01.540
And so we can't
make people change.

00:58:01.540 --> 00:58:03.950
But we can demonstrate,
through own insights,

00:58:03.950 --> 00:58:06.190
our own manifestation, and
our own self-expression,

00:58:06.190 --> 00:58:08.430
a different path
of doing things.

00:58:08.430 --> 00:58:10.250
You can't force
anybody to do anything.

00:58:10.250 --> 00:58:13.070
But you can surround
them with love

00:58:13.070 --> 00:58:15.460
and not make them
wrong for that.

00:58:15.460 --> 00:58:18.880
At the essence, this
is a path of love.

00:58:18.880 --> 00:58:21.180
And there's things that look
like self-expression which

00:58:21.180 --> 00:58:23.894
are actually, in Buddha dharma,
they would call egohood,

00:58:23.894 --> 00:58:25.810
which, you're actually--
you think that you're

00:58:25.810 --> 00:58:27.476
moving towards
enlightenment, but you're

00:58:27.476 --> 00:58:30.580
moving towards-- it's
almost like megamaniacal.

00:58:30.580 --> 00:58:32.352
So great question.

00:58:32.352 --> 00:58:33.810
AUDIENCE: In the
workspace, I would

00:58:33.810 --> 00:58:35.690
notice that a lot of
people are working

00:58:35.690 --> 00:58:38.750
from this egomaniacal space.

00:58:38.750 --> 00:58:40.300
They're working
for self-interest.

00:58:40.300 --> 00:58:41.799
They're working to
try to get ahead.

00:58:41.799 --> 00:58:44.420
They're working to try to
make a name for themselves.

00:58:44.420 --> 00:58:47.700
How does one who is trying
to work from a deeper

00:58:47.700 --> 00:58:51.590
place, trying to
express big self,

00:58:51.590 --> 00:58:54.300
do that amongst all
these other influences?

00:58:56.970 --> 00:59:00.865
AUSTIN HILL SHAW: Well,
I think that-- one

00:59:00.865 --> 00:59:02.240
of the ways of
understanding this

00:59:02.240 --> 00:59:04.850
is that I think that,
again, none of us

00:59:04.850 --> 00:59:06.540
go through our
childhood unscathed.

00:59:06.540 --> 00:59:08.560
None of us come into
the world unscathed.

00:59:08.560 --> 00:59:11.780
We have the imprints of
our maternal lineage,

00:59:11.780 --> 00:59:12.910
our paternal lineage.

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:17.080
And I also think that when
consciousness comes in,

00:59:17.080 --> 00:59:20.410
there's other elements that
are probably not even our own.

00:59:20.410 --> 00:59:22.480
They're things that are
being passed down to us

00:59:22.480 --> 00:59:24.790
that we are here to work on.

00:59:24.790 --> 00:59:28.680
And my understanding is,
basically, our core wound, what

00:59:28.680 --> 00:59:30.560
hurts us the most--
for me, it was

00:59:30.560 --> 00:59:35.060
feeling disconnected-- starts
to become your vocation.

00:59:35.060 --> 00:59:38.590
So if you sit with that feeling
of what's not working for you

00:59:38.590 --> 00:59:41.810
and be curious about
it, that's what

00:59:41.810 --> 00:59:44.590
evolves into what your vocation,
the thing you're offering.

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:46.850
So for example, here, in the
realm of the bodhisattva,

00:59:46.850 --> 00:59:50.550
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH], is
shown with thousands of eyes.

00:59:50.550 --> 00:59:54.050
And those eyes are to look out
at the suffering of the world,

00:59:54.050 --> 00:59:55.930
to understand the
suffering of the world.

00:59:55.930 --> 00:59:59.640
When you're here, the word
is basically, make your world

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:02.120
a seeming paradise
while you feel

01:00:02.120 --> 01:00:04.560
the pain of habitual patterns.

01:00:04.560 --> 01:00:06.850
This is the place
of sad joy, which

01:00:06.850 --> 01:00:10.410
is actually an amazing,
amazing place to be.

01:00:10.410 --> 01:00:13.720
The movie "Inside Out" explores
the theme of sadness and joy

01:00:13.720 --> 01:00:14.410
together.

01:00:14.410 --> 01:00:17.720
It leads for a richer life, even
though typically, we're like,

01:00:17.720 --> 01:00:20.460
I want more joy, don't
want more sadness.

01:00:20.460 --> 01:00:23.380
I just read last
night an article

01:00:23.380 --> 01:00:25.720
on the geography of sorrow.

01:00:25.720 --> 01:00:29.930
This person asked this African
woman, why are you so joyous?

01:00:29.930 --> 01:00:32.950
She said, because I cry so much.

01:00:32.950 --> 01:00:36.730
I cry so much.

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:41.340
Our joy is accelerated
and amplified

01:00:41.340 --> 01:00:45.330
by the more that we can go
in our sorrow, our hurt, all

01:00:45.330 --> 01:00:46.530
those things.

01:00:46.530 --> 01:00:50.245
And in the workplace,
that's the conversation

01:00:50.245 --> 01:00:52.290
we're going to
start to get into.

01:00:52.290 --> 01:00:56.000
We don't want to say,
here's my work persona.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:57.420
We want to bring all of you.

01:00:57.420 --> 01:00:58.732
We're better off that way.

01:00:58.732 --> 01:01:00.190
And how we manage
that, well, we're

01:01:00.190 --> 01:01:01.773
all still figuring
that out right now,

01:01:01.773 --> 01:01:04.932
how we can be fully
human everywhere.

01:01:04.932 --> 01:01:06.140
VAN RIPER: Thank you, Austin.

01:01:06.140 --> 01:01:07.990
AUSTIN HILL SHAW: Thank you.

